# COMP421 Midterm Exam

## Student Responses

### Question 1

**(a) general semaphore:** A general semaphore is an integer synchronization variable manipulated only by atomic `wait`/`signal` operations, where its value may be any nonnegative integer and is used to control access to some quantity of a resource.

**(b) best fit:** Best fit is a contiguous-memory allocation policy that places a request into the smallest free hole that is still large enough to satisfy that request.

**(c) supervisor mode:** Supervisor mode is the privileged CPU execution mode in which the operating system may execute protected instructions and access protected hardware or memory-management state that user-mode processes may not.

**(d) race condition:** A race condition is a situation in which the correctness of a program depends on the relative timing or interleaving of concurrent operations on shared state.

**(e) multiprogramming:** Multiprogramming is the operating-system technique of keeping multiple processes in memory at once so the CPU can switch to another process whenever one cannot currently use the processor.

### Question 2

I will use a **Mesa-style monitor** with condition variables.

Assume the shared bounded buffer has capacity `N` items.

```text
monitor BufferMonitor {

    const int N = BUFFER_SIZE;
    struct item buf[N];
    int in = 0;
    int out = 0;
    int used = 0;

    condition prodQ;
    condition consQ;

    long nextProdTicket = 0;
    long prodTurn = 0;
    long nextConsTicket = 0;
    long consTurn = 0;

    int waitingProd = 0;
    int waitingCons = 0;

    /* Conceptual map: for each producer ticket, store whether it needs 1 or 2 slots. */
    int prodNeed[ ... ];

    enum { PREFER_PROD, PREFER_CONS } prefer = PREFER_PROD;

    bool ProducerCanRun(long t) {
        return (t == prodTurn)
            && (used + prodNeed[t] <= N)
            && !(
                    prefer == PREFER_CONS
                 && waitingCons > 0
                 && used > 0
               );
    }

    bool ConsumerCanRun(long t) {
        return (t == consTurn)
            && (used > 0)
            && !(
                    prefer == PREFER_PROD
                 && waitingProd > 0
                 && used + prodNeed[prodTurn] <= N
               );
    }

    /* entry procedure called by a producer */
    procedure AddToBuffer(struct item *data, int count) {
        long my;
        int k;

        /* count is guaranteed to be either 1 or 2 */
        my = nextProdTicket;
        nextProdTicket = nextProdTicket + 1;
        prodNeed[my] = count;
        waitingProd = waitingProd + 1;

        while (!ProducerCanRun(my))
            wait(prodQ);

        waitingProd = waitingProd - 1;

        /* Add this producer's 1 or 2 items contiguously. */
        for (k = 0; k < count; k = k + 1) {
            buf[in] = data[k];
            in = (in + 1) mod N;
        }
        used = used + count;
        prodTurn = prodTurn + 1;
        prefer = PREFER_CONS;

        if (waitingCons > 0 && used > 0)
            signal(consQ);
        else if (waitingProd > 0 && used + prodNeed[prodTurn] <= N)
            signal(prodQ);
    }

    /* entry procedure called by a consumer */
    procedure RemoveFromBuffer(struct item *data) {
        long my;

        my = nextConsTicket;
        nextConsTicket = nextConsTicket + 1;
        waitingCons = waitingCons + 1;

        while (!ConsumerCanRun(my))
            wait(consQ);

        waitingCons = waitingCons - 1;

        data[0] = buf[out];
        out = (out + 1) mod N;
        used = used - 1;
        consTurn = consTurn + 1;
        prefer = PREFER_PROD;

        if (waitingProd > 0 && used + prodNeed[prodTurn] <= N)
            signal(prodQ);
        else if (waitingCons > 0 && used > 0)
            signal(consQ);
    }
}
```

Why this works:

- **Mutual exclusion on the shared buffer** is provided by the monitor itself.
- A producer adds both of its items inside one monitor call, so if `count == 2` those two items are inserted contiguously with no interleaving from another producer.
- **No deadlock:** if the buffer is empty, a producer can proceed; if the buffer is full, a consumer can proceed; otherwise whichever side is both eligible and currently preferred can proceed.
- **No starvation among producers:** producers are served in FIFO ticket order, so a later 1-item producer cannot repeatedly bypass an earlier 2-item producer.
- **No starvation among consumers:** consumers are likewise served in FIFO ticket order.
- **No starvation between the two classes:** whenever both a producer and a consumer could run, the monitor alternates preference (`prefer`) after each successful operation; if the preferred side cannot currently run, the other side is allowed to run immediately.
- This still allows as much concurrency as possible outside the monitor, and whenever both classes are active it does not unnecessarily block one class forever.

### Question 3

Use only semaphores. The idea is:

- keep the number of free whiteboards in `freeBoards`,
- place each arriving group into a FIFO waiting queue,
- when boards are returned, admit as many waiting groups from the **front of the queue** as possible.

This guarantees fairness (hence no starvation), avoids deadlock, and still allows multiple groups to be in the room at the same time.

```text
semaphore mutex = 1;         /* protects all shared state below */
int freeBoards = N;          /* N >= 3 */
long nextTicket = 0;

queue Q;                     /* FIFO queue of waiting requests */
int need[ ... ];             /* need[t] is 1, 2, or 3 for request t */
semaphore gate[ ... ];       /* gate[t] is created initialized to 0 */

procedure TryToAdmit() {
    long t;

    /* mutex is already held on entry */
    while (!empty(Q) && need[front(Q)] <= freeBoards) {
        t = dequeue(Q);
        freeBoards = freeBoards - need[t];
        signal(gate[t]);
    }
}

procedure EnterRoom(int count) {
    long my;

    wait(mutex);
        my = nextTicket;
        nextTicket = nextTicket + 1;
        need[my] = count;
        gate[my] = 0;
        enqueue(Q, my);
        TryToAdmit();
    signal(mutex);

    wait(gate[my]);
}

procedure LeaveRoom(int count) {
    wait(mutex);
        freeBoards = freeBoards + count;
        TryToAdmit();
    signal(mutex);
}
```

Why this works:

- **Safety:** `freeBoards` is changed only while holding `mutex`, so no two groups can be assigned the same whiteboard(s).
- **Deadlock freedom:** no group holds one whiteboard while waiting for more; a group either waits outside `EnterRoom` or, once admitted, already has all `count` whiteboards.
- **Starvation freedom:** requests wait in FIFO order, so later groups cannot pass earlier groups indefinitely.
- **Concurrency:** `TryToAdmit()` keeps admitting waiting groups from the front of the queue as long as enough boards remain, so if several waiting groups can all fit, they are all released and may work concurrently in the room.
- The algorithm uses only semaphores (`mutex` and the `gate[t]` semaphores).

### Question 4

Let `j = 1 - i`.

#### Mutual Exclusion

**Yes**, the algorithm guarantees mutual exclusion.

Informal proof:

- A process can enter the critical section only by leaving the outer loop `while (flag[j] == 1)`.
- Therefore, if process `i` enters the critical section while process `j` is trying to enter, then at the moment `i` exits that loop, either `flag[j] != 1`, or else `j` is not actually in the competing state represented by `flag[j] == 1`.
- In particular, if one process changes its flag to `2`, then the other process's outer test `while (flag[1-i] == 1)` becomes false, so only the process whose opponent is **not** equal to `1` can proceed.
- Thus both processes cannot simultaneously get past their outer `while (flag[1-i] == 1)` tests while the other still has flag value `1`.
- So both cannot be in the critical section at the same time.

#### Progress

**Yes**, the algorithm guarantees progress.

Informal proof:

- If only one process wants to enter, then the other process has `flag == 0`, so the outer `while (flag[1-i] == 1)` is immediately false and the requesting process enters.
- If both processes want to enter, then both may set `flag = 1`, but only the process whose `turn` value is no longer current will execute the `if (turn != i)` branch, set its own flag to `2`, and wait.
